    "texts": [
     "{\"template\":\"intro\",\"texts\":[\"If you get divorced, the court may take your pension benefits into account when reaching a settlement with your ex-spouse.\"],\"link\":{\"image\":{}},\"image\":{},\"wrapped\":false}",
     "There are three different ways your pension benefits can be treated:",
     "{\"template\":\"bulletlist\",\"items\":[\"Pension sharing. The value of your pension is split between you and your ex-spouse. Your own pension will reduce and your ex-spouse will become entitled to a 'pension credit' in his or her own right. The level of the split will be determined as part of the settlement\",\"Earmarking. A portion of your pension is 'earmarked' for payment to your ex-spouse\",\"As an alternative to pension sharing or earmarking, your pension will remain intact and you and your ex-spouse will divide other assets, taking account of the value of your pension when doing so\"]}",
     "Your solicitor will be able to give you more guidance as to the different options available.",
     "You may find \u003ca href=\"http://www.divorceaid.co.uk/\"\u003ehttp://www.divorceaid.co.uk\u003c/a\u003e useful.",
     "{\"template\":\"htag\",\"level\":\"h3\",\"value\":\"What happens to my pension if I remarry?\"}",
     "Your pension will continue to be paid as normal whether you are receiving a pension in respect of your own Fund membership or are receiving an adult dependant's pension."
    ],
